graduations.comments:
I've been playing mostly Blitz over the last year and I couldn't increase my Elo after a certain level. Long games are much easier for me, which means that my Rapid Elo is still leveling off at the moment. Reaching the 1450elo on chess.com went fast.
I like the program of the Dojo very much and I am still in the process of getting the necessary books to systematically work on my progress.

It’s my second graduation!! In this cohort, I stayed less than three months! It was awesome. Two things helped me a lot: Polgar Mates in two (every single day, when I wake up, I do about 10 puzzles) and annotated classical games with colleges from dojo. Another big achievement in these months was to play one OTB classical tournament (the 3rd in my life, with more than 50 rating points gain) – I will play on October an under 1700 regional OTB tournament! I’m definitely liking the program! The community also helps me to improve my English fluency – I’m from Brazil.
I have not been 1700 in 5 years.
I found Polgar and the Dojo Classical league are what I do. I also read Silman Endgame 1-5 and wish I sparred more but don't check discord in Summer.

(+) Learnt the moves as a child then didn't play for 50 years. Restarted 6 months ago, so was very helpful to have clear guidelines and structure for what and how to learn (in particular what books/resources to use / not to use) - without this I would likely have spent most of my time on openings learned from YouTube. And the discipline of reviewing games has helped me identify things to work on (I make a point to analyse my rapid games not just the longer games - there aren't many of those)
(-) the plus and equals idea hasn't been too helpful yet. I haven't had much contact with the others in the cohort (the level of Discord activity is in general very low and I haven't done much to change that) and have not yet worked out how to get games reviewed by stronger players

I think improving on two things led me to be able to get to 1600. The first is playing longer games and then b̶r̶i̶b̶i̶n̶g̶ asking my friends nicely who are rated 2000 to tell me what I did wrong in them (openings, middlegame etc). Secondly, I think that studying endgames has helped a lot. This is mostly because this knowledge has given me the confidence to go into endgames even if they aren’t the exact theoretical ones that I have studied.

Going forward, I am pretty much only going to play over the board. I need to be at least 1600 USCF to have the slightest chance of qualifying to the MD Sweet 16. Thus, that is where I am going to focus my energies going forward. Oh! And my positional understanding is still weak. ;)

I just started but have been enjoying the ride so far. Really enjoying the structure and ticking off my tasks. I've only played a couple of longer (45+30) matches so far and was surprised at how much I enjoyed them! I assumed that they wouldn't be my cup of tea, but it's a great time and doing the postmortems/annotations afterwards is fun as well.

During the month of August, leveraging a long period of vacation, I decided to work on my biggest problem: I don’t play enough. I only have a total of 46 rapid games and 25 classic (and 1 blitz!) games on Lichess, my main platform: I need to play more.
It’s like I need perfect conditions around me to sit and play, which is not realistic, so I decided to do my Blunder Games task in a month, playing 35 Rapid 15|10 games in August. I slightly overachieved that (37 games in 31 days, 22 wins and 1 draw) and I think it was very useful. During vacations and while traveling I had to play in many non ideal conditions, useful training to play more frequently.

I put a total of 47 hours of sweat work in this cohort, out of which 27 between games and annotating games. I studied Learn to Play in the Right Way 3, it’s an awesome book and extremely appropriate at my level: it’s exactly the area where I see I needed to work, and I look forward for more “defensive tactics” books. I also did 50 painful Polgar mates in 2, I did those on Kindle on the beach, so with no real board which made them even more painful. I found the pain so refreshing, I did the set twice.

Suggestions for the Dojo? Just one, not new: keep working on how to make games within the cohort happen, sparring games and Classic or Rapid 15|10 tournaments. Dojo’s main structure is already excellent, the principles are clear and sound, the materials selection (and sequence) is outstanding. With more interaction within the cohort, the feeling of “being part of a Dojo” will be much stronger.
Current USCF is 1923
Love studying the Morphy games in a first book of Morphy. Very inspiring!

I'm Andrew (he/him) and I'm excited for my first graduation. I started playing OTB at Mechanics' Institute in SF after a 30-year break from chess and I struggled initially with nerves/clock/scoresheets. But my most recent tournament performance was USCF 877, and I've completed a majority of the 700-800 cohort sweat work, so I'm ready to soar higher!

I appreciated the focus that came from sticking to the selected duo of tactics books (Polgar and EFCW). As a type-A personality, the Dojo Scoreboard is a big motivator to #dothework — I'm pushed to study by a desire to see my Dojo score increase, so this gamification is a big benefit of the training program. 

My missing link is currently the sparring work — family life makes it hard to join the sparring tournaments, but I definitely see the value. Especially as it applies to converting winning positions OTB, which I've struggled with. I see there are new efforts to tweak the sparring arenas, so hopefully I'll be able to join those more regularly.

The biggest benefit of the training program for me is the Dojo community — having focused equal players to schedule online Classical games with (where one can rely on a good challenge), the plus players to review my games (notes/voice), the minus players that offer their games for me to explain my advice. I've met other Dojo members at my home club, and it's fun to prep with and root for them during tournaments.

Thanks to Jesse and Kostya and David for creating this thing, and to everyone in the Dojo for showing up day in day out. Onward ...

Additional Tactics, as well as some further guidance on game analysis/annotation.  It's clearly a learned skill, but further fundamental instruction may be beneficial (in addition to the already existing senses videos).
Blunder games have encouraged me to play a lot more and not care so much about winning or losing

The good - loving the program structure, making me play long games, annotate and do the blunder games - I've been playing a lot more with less stress since I joined the dojo
The needs improvement - hard to get cohort games, being in Australia doesn't help, hoping the dojo keeps growing so volume solves this somewhat

I think the program has been great. I need to be better at engaging with it more though. Especially with the rest of the community. I also had to take quite a bit of time away from chess so I'm hoping to get back on it so will do my best to make time for cohort training.
Back after five month hiatus.  Looking to start a tier fresh.
I have just started the programme; therefore, my graduation at this stage relates to a rating adjustment. That said, although it's early days, I am enjoying the dojo and see it improving my game!

The Polgar book is amazing. I have won some games from spotting mates I wouldn't have seen before, but more importantly my board vision has improved quite a bit from the puzzles. Looking forward to keep playing and improving. 
(I mentioned this last time I graduated as well, but from the games I've played vs randos on Lichess I think the Lichess- to FIDE-rating estimation needs tweaking. :) )

Here we go again, the hard work finally pays off. Second graduation in 3 weeks, unfortunatelly this is due to the DWZ rating system which comes in delayed usually (end of season updates or after tournaments). After a 7 round tournament I made it to over 1400. Will get my first Fide ELO soon as well. 
Btw: Jesse, in the grad show last time you put the question: I play for a lower team (Kreisliga) at SC Noris-Tarrasch Nürnberg 1873. Relatively many younger player and more than 150 members helps finding something like a cohort.
Comments same as last time, play long time controls, analyze (and publish annotations, this is crucial for the quality!) is most helpful.

I was practically at graduation when I joined, so I didn't get the chance to learn much, although I had my first proper no engine game review in this cohort, and I learned a lot from it! I promised myself I would at least do that before I played the last rapid game I needed for graduation.

I enjoyed the 1100-1200 section of the program, but I feel as if there should be more endgames in the lichess endgame tasks.. A lot of my points came from endgames despite not having to spend long on them. Perhaps that is just my endgame being better than the average 1200, but either way I feel like a few extra tasks would've been nice.
No comments really, very enjoyable cohort. :)

Really liked to play my first ever classical chess game! Couldn't find the time to do the drills for the endgame unfortunately, but overall it gives me a road to follow (or not) and I really like this dojo!

The progress bars help me a lot to keep me motivated and to actually do training. What could be improved is the guide on how to analyse games, since I'm still very uncertain most of the timea if my analysis is how it should be. Another thing that should be improved is the ease in getting sparring games. Although you can get some sparring games, most people are doing another thing which makes it difficult to get a game where you spar what you want to train. Maybe something that automatically suggests people to spar on a specific subject.
Enormously helpful all round. Love the program and it's been greatly helpful.

This is my first "true" graduation, the structure and accountability of the program has been very helpful. The polgar mates and everyone's first chess workbook have been helpful. The plus, equal and minus has been helpful. In closing I would like to say thank you all for the dojo program and have a great day.

I prefer using my OTB rating (Finnish rating system which seems to be quite close to the USCF rating in terms of the distance from FIDE ratings) to measure my progress in classical play but the problem is I'm only getting to play one game every 2-4 weeks and my rating is still provisional (only started OTB play in March). However, I feel I'm improving in shorter time controls as well and definitely feeling the effects of going through the Chernev books in my understanding of the game.
